title: For Sale:  Pair of 1847 Colt Walkers 150th Anniversary Edition NIB
postcontent: A pair of consective serial number 1847 Colt Walkers - Signature Series - 150th Anniversary Edition 1847-1997.  Both new in box and unused/unfired.  Price is for the pair.0.44 calibre largest revolver to carry the Colt name.  9" barrels and weighing 4lb 9oz each.  In 1846 at Fort McHenry, Army Captain Samuel Hamilton Walker urged Samuel Colt to produce a powerful weapon to improve upon the Patterson.  The 1847 Walker was developed for the Mounted Riflemen (Dragoons) that Walker was recruiting for the Mexican War.  Handles 50 balls per pound of lead making for a lethal close rnage weapon more accurate than what had come before.  Colt produced 1,100 of the original revolvers marked for Dragoon Companies A, B, C, D and E.  The Colt Signature Series 150th Anniversary reissue of this model bears markings identical to the original - "US 1847" over the barrel wedge and "A Company No.1" in gold to commemorate the first Dragoon Company to carry the Walker into battle.  Not a replica.  Deeply blued finished cylinder and protective coating on brass trigger guard.  The famous battle scene engraved on the cylinders is as originally witnessed by Walker between 15 Texas Rangers and a Comanche war party and is precisely as engraved in 1847 by O. L. Ormsby.

title: For Sale:  Finnish M91, New England Westinghouse, excellent!
postcontent: This is a M91 with quite a long history (TOP RIFLE PICTURED)!  Produced in the USA at the Meridan factory by New England Westinghouse for Russia sometime between 1915 and 1918, then acquired by the Finnish Army and at some point loaned to the Finnish Civil Guard (SS number).  The number links this one to the Vilpuri District, home of the famous Finnish sniper, Simo Hayha ("White Death").  Eventually it was sent back to the Finnish Army (lined out SS district number) where it was likely refurbished and put into storage.  Condition is like new, with an excellent shiny bore.  **CHECK OUT MY OTHER LISTINGS**$425 picked up in Findlay, OH
